commit_message:
Change the sample_type from tuple to string

The Collector can not persistence compute node CPU metrics when set
‘compute_monitors = ComputeDriverCPUMonitor’ in nova.
The root cause of that issue is the counter_type is the 'tuple',
In actually the type of the counter_type should be String,
so it can not persistence to DB success, please refer to the SQL,
the counter_type value is [u'cumulative'] that is a 'tuple'.

Change-Id: I8d1218f813d081e1031c331c59a17c227c9a8958
Closes-Bug: #1295004

commit_message:
Catch NotImplementedError on Network Associate

When trying to associate/disassociate a network both for project/host
using neutron a 500 error is returned because the "associate" method is
not even defined in neutronv2 api.

The changes are:
   * Add missing associate method to neutronv2 api and raise
     NotImplementedError
   * Catch NotImplementedError on the API to return the proper error
     code on network associate/disassociate operations.
   * Catch NotImplementedError on os_network when associating a network

Closes-Bug: #1293539
Change-Id: I75b980500f0f171b065b7606baf201ab89848e92

commit_message:
Make os-refresh-config install.d hook run later

os-refresh-config relies on being able to run virtualenv, which is only
guaranteed to be possible after running 01-install-pip from the
pip-and-virtualenv element.

To guarantee this ordering, move
install.d/os-refresh-config-source-install/01-os-refresh-config to
install.d/os-refresh-config-source-install/10-os-refresh-config

And for consistency in script execution timing, move
install.d/os-refresh-config-package-install/01-os-refresh-config to
install.d/os-refresh-config-package-install/10-os-refresh-config

Change-Id: I3b0a127c0c6eca16854f84a3c733cbd54c8a4880
Closes-Bug: #1292514

commit_message:
Remove many references to github

OpenStack's primary git repositories aren't on github, so update the
URLs en-masse to point to git.o.o. There are some references left as
they either reference code that is only on github, or require it,
like the Jenkins element.

commit_message:
Tidy up urlfetch.py exception handling

IOError doesn't seem appropiate for things like invalid URL scheme
and template exceeding max size. And requests.RequestException means
an ambiguous exception occurred while handling requests, not
necessarily an IO error.

revisions:
[{'number': 3, 'created': '2014-03-19 03:34:27.000000000', 'files': ['neutron/tests/unit/metaplugin/test_metaplugin.py', 'neutron/plugins/metaplugin/meta_neutron_plugin.py', 'neutron/plugins/metaplugin/common/config.py', 'etc/neutron/plugins/metaplugin/metaplugin.ini'], 'message': "Enable to select an RPC handling plugin under Metaplugin

Multiple plugins under metaplugin become 'q-plugin' topic
consumers and a request from an agent is handled by one of
them randomly. Fortunatly most of RPC callbacks are common
for plugins but a problem occurs if an RPC is not supported
by the received plugin.

This is one of risks when using metaplugin. Fundamental fix
of this problem (such as RPC delegation handling of metaplugin)
is difficult since each plugin needs to modify.
But when only one plugin has plugin specific RPCs and other
RPCs are independet of plugins, if the plugin can be selected
for RPC handling, the problem does not happen. Typical use
case of metaplugin such as combination of an agent-based
plugin and a controller-based plugin often applies to this
condition.

This patch adds 'rpc_flavor' configuration parameter to
select an RPC handling plugin. If 'rpc_flavor' is specified,
only the specified plugin becomes 'q-plugin' topic consumer.
If 'rpc_flavor' is not specified, the behavior is same as
previous one.

Change-Id: If133b054bba53829cebe63c1e0ebe6099eb1fd95
Closes-bug: #1267330
DocImpact
"}]
commit_message:
Enable to select an RPC handling plugin under Metaplugin

Multiple plugins under metaplugin become 'q-plugin' topic
consumers and a request from an agent is handled by one of
them randomly. Fortunatly most of RPC callbacks are common
for plugins but a problem occurs if an RPC is not supported
by the received plugin.

This is one of risks when using metaplugin. Fundamental fix
of this problem (such as RPC delegation handling of metaplugin)
is difficult since each plugin needs to modify.
But when only one plugin has plugin specific RPCs and other
RPCs are independet of plugins, if the plugin can be selected
for RPC handling, the problem does not happen. Typical use
case of metaplugin such as combination of an agent-based
plugin and a controller-based plugin often applies to this
condition.

This patch adds 'rpc_flavor' configuration parameter to
select an RPC handling plugin. If 'rpc_flavor' is specified,
only the specified plugin becomes 'q-plugin' topic consumer.
If 'rpc_flavor' is not specified, the behavior is same as
previous one.

Change-Id: If133b054bba53829cebe63c1e0ebe6099eb1fd95
Closes-bug: #1267330
DocImpact

commit_message:
Update selinux policies for mysqld

mysqld fails to startup when selinux is in enforcing mode. This is
because the data and logs were moved under /mnt/state and the selinux
policies were not updated to allow mysql access to the new locations.

Change-Id: I5ccf1078ad0edc066bab430580886ed6c253e153

commit_message:
Trove Manual Installation guide

Installation of Trove on a VM different from the controller node.
The openstack environment is Havana.
The Keystone service accepts only HTTPS connections.

According to the redstack script:
 - commands related to the datastore creation/configuration are updated.
 - details on the configuration files are provided.

commit_message:
Add update binding:profile with physical_network

Add temporary solution in order to support multiple physical networks
by mlnx ML2 MechanismDriver.
Due to non merged patches in nova that should support propagating
physical_network retrieved from port binding:profile attribute
to VIF/Network object.
The code will be removed once relevant nova patches are merged.
The code is disabled by default and should be enabled via
ml2_conf_mlnx.ini config file.

Change-Id: I815f9e28774efd47bccd1c57481e6ba89075792b
Closes-bug: #1291209

commit_message:
Unwedge stable branch: stop syncing trove and fix pypy

Remove trove from requirements sync in havana. Trove wasn't actually
part of the integrated release in havana,
so it's not getting actively maintained on the backports. Remove
it from requirements sync to help unwedge stable.

pypy is blocking all requirements merge at the moment, which is
problematic as we've got some changes that should land prior to
icehouse. Implement the work around that fungi posted to IRC by
backporting the tox.ini from master.

Depends on: Iab4ae1efddc4dca38dcd3779dae1a79ddc2b0852

Co-Authored-By: Sean Dague <sean.dague@samsung.com>
Co-Authored-By: Sergey Lukjanov <slukjanov@mirantis.com>
Change-Id: Ib2e2aa2e75e7b7b43e0534eeb62e748d1edc0bc3

This middleware is spamming rsyslog with rabbitmq debug logs, making
this middleware practically unusable in combination with rsyslog. Because of
this, the rsyslog logs now account for 35% percent of the logs we store
in logstash. Until the underlying problem is solved disable the
offending code.

Related-Bug: #1294789
"}]
commit_message:
Disable ceilometer's swift middleware

This middleware is spamming rsyslog with rabbitmq debug logs, making
this middleware practically unusable in combination with rsyslog. Because of
this, the rsyslog logs now account for 35% percent of the logs we store
in logstash. Until the underlying problem is solved disable the
offending code.

Change-Id: I50a73ae6beb1a11c41225340779fe8d7a1081e46
Related-Bug: #1294789

commit_message:
Validate get fixed-ips attributes of Nova V2 API

This patch adds the JSON schema for Nova V2 get fixed-ips API
response and validate the response with added JSON schema to
block the backward incompatibility change in the future.

The response body of V2 get fixed-ip API is below:

{
    "fixed_ip": {
        "address": "192.168.1.1",
        "cidr": "192.168.1.0/24",
        "host": "host",
        "hostname": "openstack"
    }
}

Partially implements blueprint nova-api-attribute-test

commit_message:
Stop running pip install -U when installing deps.

The pip install -U should only be necessary when site packages are
enabled. Novaclient doesn't need site packages enabled for any of its
dependencies so we can avoid the upgrade step during dep installation.

Removing the upgrade step is necessary to prevent pip on pypy from
breaking setuptools during dependency installation.

Note this does mean tests run on not latest version of everything.

Change-Id: I36a990e280832d399480e7f63dd7527e4b16e51e

commit_message:
Validate of Nova list Floating IPs attributes

This patch adds the JSON schema for Nova list Floating IPs API
response and validate the response of list Floating IPs API
with added JSON schema to block the backward incompatibility
change in the future.

The response body of list Floating IPs API is below:

{
    "floating_ips": [
        {
            "id": 1,
            "pool": "nova",
            "instance_id": null,
            "ip": "10.10.10.1",
            "fixed_ip": null,
        }
    ]
}

Partially implements blueprint nova-api-attribute-test

Change-Id: Ica266688af310bb804bcf7fb240ca6a005b156c0

commit_message:
Increase the default pip socket timeout

pip's default timeout of 15 seconds doesn't seem to be high enough
causing us to intermittently fail getting the pypi index. Increasing
the timeout in an attempt to make it less likely to hit the problem.

Change-Id: Ic5c85765e5cce9ccabcabc277b6e8f59b4451cdc
Related-Bug: #1272417

commit_message:
Ensure alarm rule conform to alarm type

Threshold_rule or combination_rule must be set to an Alarm object,
and they cannot be set at the same time.
Alarm's type must be one of threshold and combination.
Threshold_rule and combination_rule should be validated according alarm's
type.

Change-Id: I97bf82defeaf0dc1a0e897e10886fd736361041d
Closes-bug: #1288677

commit_message:
Add deleted_at attribute in glance stub on delete()

The glance stub used in unit tests sets the 'deleted' attribute to
True for the deleted image, but does not also add the 'deleted_at'
attribute, which should also be included, since that's how glance
actually operates. 'deleted_at' is missing from a few other places
as well; add it there for consistency.

Change-Id: I60a96f568d45a4f5fabdb146e0028c4cf680b9fa

revisions:
[{'number': 3, 'created': '2014-03-14 02:04:38.000000000', 'files': ['tempest/api/network/admin/test_dhcp_agent_scheduler.py'], 'message': 'Fix error trace induced by dhcp test actions

Once the agent is removed, we are unable to deallocate
dhcp resources for the port until the entire network is
torn down; this is fine, but by doing so we cause Neutron
Server to emit a log error.

This patch simply deletes the port before doing the
disassociation, however a cleaner way to deal with this
would be to avoid relying on port creation to trigger a

commit_message:
Fix error trace induced by dhcp test actions

Once the agent is removed, we are unable to deallocate
dhcp resources for the port until the entire network is
torn down; this is fine, but by doing so we cause Neutron
Server to emit a log error.

This patch simply deletes the port before doing the
disassociation, however a cleaner way to deal with this
would be to avoid relying on port creation to trigger a
network scheduling, though, this would require a more
elaborated fix.

Closes-bug: 1292242

commit_message:
Catch FloatingIpNotFoundForHost exception

When showing floating ips for a given host, the FloatingIpNotFoundForHost
exception isn't handled when no floating ips can be found for the host.
This patch fixes this bug.

Closes-Bug: #1289164
Change-Id: Ic25ffd66945fd40ba10d69515e0cbfeae840313c

subject: Explicity set default notifier strategy
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2014-03-19 21:36:38.000000000', 'files': ['manifests/api.pp'], 'message': 'Explicity set default notifier strategy

Havana claims to set this to the default, but in reality it does not. The default is actually set to qpid because oslo.config automically looks for default options in /usr/share/glance/glance-api-dist.conf, which in turn sets `notifier_strategy = qpid`.

Later version of oslo.config seem to have fixed this behavior and do not load *-dist* config files.

Change-Id: Ib69c8f322b1309c0280364f0639fa6edff36262d
'}]
commit_message:
Explicity set default notifier strategy

Havana claims to set this to the default, but in reality it does not. The default is actually set to qpid because oslo.config automically looks for default options in /usr/share/glance/glance-api-dist.conf, which in turn sets `notifier_strategy = qpid`.

Later version of oslo.config seem to have fixed this behavior and do not load *-dist* config files.

Change-Id: Ib69c8f322b1309c0280364f0639fa6edff36262d

commit_message:
BigSwitch: Sync workaround for port del deadlock

Adds a synchronization barrier to the methods
that lock the port table to avoid the mysql
update-lock/eventlet-yield deadlock that occurs
with simultaneous port deletions.

Closes-Bug: #1292232
Change-Id: I8975a14a937a5843a0395ad7b599ebdc827565ed

subject: Modify stack ID lookup to only use stacks:lookup
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2014-03-14 15:35:43.000000000', 'files': ['heatclient/common/http.py', 'heatclient/v1/stacks.py'], 'message': "Modify stack ID lookup to only use stacks:lookup

Currently when we lookup a stack ID (fully qualified name/id) via
stacks:lookup, we also follow the redirect to stacks:show, which
is not allowed for stack users.  We don't actually need to follow
the redirect, as we already have the required ID, so instead we
return the redirect response, so we can just allow all users to
do stacks:lookup in the policy.

This is useful for clients who want to call API actions which are
allowed for stack users, e.g resource:signal without having to know
both the name and ID of the stack.

Change-Id: I6f079cbc7ac3c680f15941668b4efbe4c3c5d60d
Partial-Bug: #1291097
"}]
commit_message:
Modify stack ID lookup to only use stacks:lookup

Currently when we lookup a stack ID (fully qualified name/id) via
stacks:lookup, we also follow the redirect to stacks:show, which
is not allowed for stack users.  We don't actually need to follow
the redirect, as we already have the required ID, so instead we
return the redirect response, so we can just allow all users to
do stacks:lookup in the policy.

This is useful for clients who want to call API actions which are
allowed for stack users, e.g resource:signal without having to know
both the name and ID of the stack.

Change-Id: I6f079cbc7ac3c680f15941668b4efbe4c3c5d60d
Partial-Bug: #1291097

commit_message:
WIP: Assembly creation actions

    Added code to perform following actions when assembly create is called:
     - Parse plan 'raw_content' field to get artifact name and git_url
       The image builder service requires these attributes to build the DU.
     - Call the image builder service to build the DU.

    Also updated the trigger_workflow with the following code:
     - Using trigger_id get the assemby and plan objects.
     - Call the above mentioned code for parsing the plan and building the DU.

Change-Id: Ifd7ce022df40e7c0828bdcb475f79131ce16f5dd

commit_message:
Catch HostBinaryNotFound exception in V2 API

When updating a service with a wrong host or binary name,
HostBinaryNotFound exception will be raised.
However the ServiceNotFound exception which won't happen here
is caught instead of HostBinaryNotFound.
The similar fix has been merged in V3 API.
I64b138bad74c39d087addcd766b890c4076a2ce8

Change-Id: I37cf7a56c5478bb1273ef038bb197d80af0ae7b5
Closes-Bug: #1273139

commit_message:
NSX: Sync do not pass around model object

The NSX sync backend previously passed around a sqlalchemy model object
around which was nice because we did not need to query the database an
additional time to update the status of an object.

Unfortunately, this was add done within a db transaction which included a
call to NSX which could cause deadlock this needed to be removed. Now a
dict is passed around instead and proper transaction handling
is used when updating objects.

Change-Id: Id50abd8f2143b127d1ca81c360c1c6d400e1d74f
Closes-bug: #1281772

commit_message:
Checking the type of auth_token, and fixing it if necessary

When creating a new Client object by calling the get_client function,
if the ceilometer_url is not passed as a parameter, but the token is
passed, the auth_token is converted to a lambda function.
However, when both the ceilometer_url and the auth_token are passed,
this conversion does not take place.
This fix checks if the auth_token is a lambda function or not.
If it is not, it creates a new lambda function which returns the
token.
Without this check, if a token was passed as a string, the
python client would throw and error, when trying to call
self.auth_token() in ceilomenterclient/common/http.py.

Change-Id: I3e564fcf17ce497546b75f0ab8c7ca0f6f2099df
Closes-Bug: #1254186

commit_message:
Increase the default pip socket timeout

pip's default timeout of 15 seconds doesn't seem to be high enough
causing us to intermittently fail getting the pypi index. Increasing
the timeout in an attempt to make it less likely to hit the problem.

Related-Bug: #1292141
Change-Id: I5ecf009259b76973228c86ada7859b7897892956

commit_message:
Webhook DB schema and object model

- Removed trigger_id attribute from assembly DB schema.
- Added a new table 'webhook' with attributes - trigger_id, plan_id & assembly_id.

Currently trigger_id is an attribute in the assembly table.
However, trigger_id will be generated when we POST to plan (i.e while registering
the plan). At this time, the assembly does not exist, so we need to associate the
trigger_id with the plan and once the assembly is created, the trigger_id would
be associated with the assembly.
We will also be adding a separate 'webhook' API resource.

[Note: Read the entire discussion here - https://botbot.me/freenode/solum/msg/12219803/]

Change-Id: Iac633dccddb241e2997abde727517ec32eb519e0

commit_message:
Add RequestContextSerializer for rpc notifications

RequestContext should be serialized when sent via oslo.messaging. The
serializer is correctly used for the general RPC mechanism, but has been
forgotten in the notifier. This patch fixes that.

Thanks goes to eharney for noticing this and pointing it out!!!

Same bug existed in Nova (1275771)

Change-Id: I99a571ef74bbcd13bf801313eea145ea69f821e1
Closes-Bug: #1294724

commit_message:
Fix race on container recreate

There was a path on container recreate that would sometimes allow db to get
reinitialized without updating put_timestamp.  Replication would of course fix
it up, but that node would think it's database was deleted till then desipite
just ok'ing a request with a newer X-Timestamp than the deleted_timestamp on
disk.

Change-Id: I8b98afb2aac2e433b6ecb5c421ba0d778cef42fa
Closes-Bug: #1292784

subject: Reverting default keystone API to v2.0
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2014-03-18 23:26:06.000000000', 'files': ['openstack_auth/utils.py'], 'message': 'Reverting default keystone API to v2.0

Although keystone v2 has been deprecated, no services use v3 for
authorization. So passing a v3 token_id to other services results
in authorization errors. If the user logs into a domain other than
"default" the user see only unauthorized errors. Currently, when
logging into the "default" domain these authorization errors do not
occur merely because of a bug in keystone that does not validate
the token version. This will likely change some time in the
non-distant future.

Setting the keystone API version to v2.0 is the safest path for now.

Not doing a full revert because the rest of the fixes the previous
patch were valid and required.

Closes-Bug: #1294396
Change-Id: I3583e729b5a006f9b7f5cbbe3388908c15de39ae
'}]
commit_message:
Reverting default keystone API to v2.0

Although keystone v2 has been deprecated, no services use v3 for
authorization. So passing a v3 token_id to other services results
in authorization errors. If the user logs into a domain other than
"default" the user see only unauthorized errors. Currently, when
logging into the "default" domain these authorization errors do not
occur merely because of a bug in keystone that does not validate
the token version. This will likely change some time in the
non-distant future.

Setting the keystone API version to v2.0 is the safest path for now.

Not doing a full revert because the rest of the fixes the previous
patch were valid and required.

Closes-Bug: #1294396
Change-Id: I3583e729b5a006f9b7f5cbbe3388908c15de39ae

commit_message:
Make optional dependencies in tests optional

Optional dependencies in the test suite were not actually optional
once they were imported because the _factories dictionary was always
referenced to determine if there was a potential provider to
intantiate. This list was never cleared. To correct this the _factories
dictionary has been removed and tests that expect an optional dependency
now instantiate the Manager. The full registry from the dependency module
is used to populate the *_api properties on the test cases.

Unlike the other optional providers, revoke_api was not instantiated when
the routes were added. Added into this change includes fix to instantiate
the revoke_api manager in the add_routes method to ensure dependency
injection works properly.

Change-Id: Ibb660d34c5ef206b0c5416354fb799275c482f75

commit_message:
Remove Copyright holder line from template

The important part is the Apache2 header not who holds the copyright.
These copyright holder lines are often inaccurate and misleading, so
don't require one by default.

Note: Some companies require there employees to use these, so if someone
adds this line in there spec, we should allow it. We just don't want to
require one by default.

Change-Id: Ifd82752d4e220360ab1d8a6bcd3fc27cb10b7d65

commit_message:
Make compute API resize methods use Quotas objects

The compute API's various resize methods are using the old-style quota
class to reserve and commit quota changes directly to the database. This
change uses quotas objects to do the reserve and commit instead so those
operations go through conductor for the database access.

Note that the long-term goal is to pass the quota object over RPC
rather than the reservations list, but that's a larger patch which
is not necessary for the bug fix.

Closes-Bug: #1262461

Change-Id: Id18357f449193d25287f32bb8ffbf26ee2194a22

commit_message:
Refuse to block migrate instances with config drive

libvirt does not block migrate read only devices such as config
drives. It decides that the config drive is read only because it
is attached as a cdrom. So, we just throw our hands up in the
air and bravely refuse to block migrate those instances.

Partial-Bug: 1246201

Change-Id: I24f4f83c1ddf1cf3e37db4663ab82e61f0a2d00f
DocImpact: you should read all that stuff above.

commit_message:
BigSwitch: Use eventlet.sleep in watchdog

Changes the consistency watchdog that runs
in the background to use eventlet.sleep instead
of time.sleep to avoid blocking other members of

actually raising one, there is no return value to the method. This can

accurate.

commit_message:
Process ICMP type for iptables firewall

In current security group code, source_port_range_min
and source_port_range_max are used to specify icmp type
and code when security group rule protocol is icmp.
However, the code _port_arg in iptables_firewall called
by _convert_sgr_to_iptables_rules skips protocol icmp
when processing the arg. This happens to both ipv4 and
ipv6 icmp firewall rules.

This fix adds --icmp-type to iptables firewall rule when
icmp type is specified.

Closes-Bug: 1289088

Change-Id: Iebf109f246d47cffc26ab3c2cf113234a4b2cffe

commit_message:
ML2 BigSwitch: Don't modify parent context

Makes a copy of the port context before changing
it in preparation for the backend controller so
other drivers are not affected. Also removes a
UT that was exercising direct modification of VIF
details in the port context, which is not allowed
by the ML2 plugin.

Closes-Bug: #1294308
Change-Id: I47281dcd23c022813b8b6eda0a3d39c4482277b9

commit_message:
BigSwitch: Widen range of HTTPExceptions caught

In order to trigger a reconnect, the Big Switch
plugin was only checking for httplib.ImproperConnectionState
which doesn't include relevant exceptions that
indicate a reconnect is necessary. This patch
adjusts it to reconnect on any HTTPException.

Closes-Bug: #1289236
Change-Id: I4b389172dc4a53b0381e40005d8421f71b7d8522

commit_message:
Fix KeyError if neutron security group is not TCP/UDP/ICMP and no ports

Previously, if a neutron security group rule was created that was not
TCP/UDP/ICMP and did not contain a port_range_min/max retrieving it from
nova-api would result in a KeyError in nova-api. This patch resolves

subject: Allow pre-1970 dates in If-[Un]Modified-Since
reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 1009, 'name': 'Greg Lange', 'email': 'greglange@gmail.com', 'username': 'greglange'}, {'_account_id': 2622, 'name': 'Samuel Merritt', 'email': 'sam@swiftstack.com', 'username': 'torgomatic'}, {'_account_id': 6198, 'name': 'Peter Portante', 'email': 'peter.a.portante@gmail.com', 'username': 'peter-a-portante'}, {'_account_id': 6968, 'name': 'Christian Schwede', 'email': 'cschwede@redhat.com', 'username': 'cschwede'}, {'_account_id': 10378, 'name': 'Luis de Bethencourt', 'email': 'luis@debethencourt.com', 'username': 'luisbg'}]
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2014-03-15 01:00:57.000000000', 'files': ['swift/obj/server.py', 'test/unit/obj/test_server.py', 'swift/common/swob.py', 'test/unit/common/test_swob.py'], 'message': 'Allow pre-1970 dates in If-[Un]Modified-Since

If I want to fetch an object only if it is newer than the first moon
landing, I send a GET request with header:

    If-Modified-Since: Sun, 20 Jul 1969 20:18:00 UTC

Since that date is older than Swift, I expect a 2xx response. However,
I get a 412, which isn't even a valid thing to do for
If-Modified-Since; it should either be 2xx or 304. This is because of
two problems:

(a) Swift treats pre-1970 dates as invalid, and

(b) Swift returns 412 when a date is invalid instead of ignoring it.

This commit makes it so any time between datetime.datetime.min and
datetime.datetime.max is an acceptable value for If-Modified-Since and
If-Unmodified-Since. Dates outside that date range are treated as
invalid headers and thus are ignored, as RFC 2616 section 14.28
requires ("If the specified date is invalid, the header is ignored").

This only works for dates that the Python standard library can parse,
which on my machine is 01 Jan 1 to 31 Dec 9999. Eliminating those
restrictions would require implementing our own date parsing and
comparison, and that's almost certainly not worth it.

Change-Id: I4cb4903c4e5e3b6b3c9506c2cabbfbda62e82f35
'}]
commit_message:
Allow pre-1970 dates in If-[Un]Modified-Since

If I want to fetch an object only if it is newer than the first moon
landing, I send a GET request with header:

    If-Modified-Since: Sun, 20 Jul 1969 20:18:00 UTC

Since that date is older than Swift, I expect a 2xx response. However,
I get a 412, which isn't even a valid thing to do for
If-Modified-Since; it should either be 2xx or 304. This is because of
two problems:

(a) Swift treats pre-1970 dates as invalid, and

(b) Swift returns 412 when a date is invalid instead of ignoring it.

This commit makes it so any time between datetime.datetime.min and
datetime.datetime.max is an acceptable value for If-Modified-Since and
If-Unmodified-Since. Dates outside that date range are treated as
invalid headers and thus are ignored, as RFC 2616 section 14.28
requires ("If the specified date is invalid, the header is ignored").

This only works for dates that the Python standard library can parse,
which on my machine is 01 Jan 1 to 31 Dec 9999. Eliminating those
restrictions would require implementing our own date parsing and
comparison, and that's almost certainly not worth it.

Change-Id: I4cb4903c4e5e3b6b3c9506c2cabbfbda62e82f35

revisions:

This patch fixes bug 1292519.  Some install packages were listed
  that were not available in the repositories used for the HDP
  image installs.
Some of these packages were only valid for HDP 1.3, and so have
  been removed from the HDP 2.0 install commands.
Some of the packages listed in the HDP 1.3 install were only valid
  in HDP 2.0, so these package names have been removed from the
  HDP 1.3 install.
Some packages in the HDP 1.3 install commands were incorrectly named
  and not actually required by HDP 1.3, so this patch removes those

The commands used to install mysql have been refactored into a

  installs.
This patch also removes other unavailable packages that were listed
  in warnings during the HDP image generation process.  After some
  investigation, it was determined that these packages were either

Change-Id: I77eddf4497116d578720e9aaacba386333789757
'}]
commit_message:
Removes unnecessary/incorectly-named packages from HDP install script

This patch fixes bug 1292519.  Some install packages were listed
  that were not available in the repositories used for the HDP
  image installs.
Some of these packages were only valid for HDP 1.3, and so have
  been removed from the HDP 2.0 install commands.
Some of the packages listed in the HDP 1.3 install were only valid
  in HDP 2.0, so these package names have been removed from the
  HDP 1.3 install.
Some packages in the HDP 1.3 install commands were incorrectly named
  and not actually required by HDP 1.3, so this patch removes those
  package names.
The commands used to install mysql have been refactored into a
  common method, which is now used by both the HDP 1.3 and 2.0
  installs.
This patch also removes other unavailable packages that were listed
  in warnings during the HDP image generation process.  After some
  investigation, it was determined that these packages were either
  incorrectly referenced, or no longer needed for HDP.

Fixes: bug # 1292519

Change-Id: I77eddf4497116d578720e9aaacba386333789757

commit_message:
Update aggregate should not allow duplicated names

It is not allow to create 2 aggregates with the same name
but if update an existing one with a name already used
by other aggregate that check should be made.
This patch doesn't allow to change the name to an existing
one.

Change-Id: Icfe315594beaec94229e5a4a4c1bb80fc366b66e
Closes-Bug: #1288296

that when we highlight a span we get the box you expect, not just
the indented portion.

commit_message:
Fix CONFIG_SCHEMA for runners

We have strict format requests for user input task configuration file.
And, we use CONFIG_SCHEMA to check the formate.
While the CONFIG_SCHEMA is not accurate, user tasks will not start.

Close-bug #1294969

Change-Id: Ib89d6a1e2dcbc951ea9fcd668f1cb503f81bc9cc

commit_message:
Base part of a server REST API

The patch introduces a first version of REST API. Rally can be run
as-a-Service by the shell script rally-api. By default a service binds
to a socket 0.0.0.0:8877. The pair of binding parameters have got own
section called an 'api'. One of the supported Content-Type is an
'application/json'.

TODO:
* A Deployment and a Task controllers/types.
* Proper exception handling.

blueprint rally-service-api-v1

Change-Id: Ib0a1f141a083a35c8d43aed2bb1db3307e022b70

subject: Usability improvements to the spec template
revisions:
[{'number': 7, 'created': '2014-03-20 11:49:05.000000000', 'files': ['template.rst'], 'message': 'Usability improvements to the spec template

Template should be easier to use with a little more structure
between the sections. Added a comment that people can add None instead
of deleting a section. This should help keep the use of the template
more consistent.

The sub-headings in implementation are renamed to match the existing
fields in launchpad. Should make parsing these easier at some point in
the future.

Tweaked the order so its closer to the current launchpad ordering.
Partly to ease the transition, party because I like the order they have
chosen.

Made a distinction between end-users, deployers and developers. This
has created much confusion in the past.

To reduce the text we force people to delete, trying out adding some
instructions as a comment block.

Change-Id: I28fae5c03da6939471109de7177ac7d2440e7680
'}]
commit_message:
Usability improvements to the spec template

Template should be easier to use with a little more structure
between the sections. Added a comment that people can add None instead
of deleting a section. This should help keep the use of the template
more consistent.

The sub-headings in implementation are renamed to match the existing
fields in launchpad. Should make parsing these easier at some point in
the future.

Tweaked the order so its closer to the current launchpad ordering.
Partly to ease the transition, party because I like the order they have
chosen.

Made a distinction between end-users, deployers and developers. This
has created much confusion in the past.

To reduce the text we force people to delete, trying out adding some
instructions as a comment block.

Change-Id: I28fae5c03da6939471109de7177ac7d2440e7680

commit_message:
NEC plugin: Honor Retry-After response from OFC

A backend OpenFlow controller nec plugin talks to can return
503 response with retry-after header when it is busy.
It is better to honor retry-after header to avoid unnecessary
user-visible errors due to temporary busy condition.

Change-Id: I2ff1c3ac8402a2207bd955e9a9bb61e147950c5c
Closes-Bug: #1294527

This patch adds a semaphore for serializing the delete port API
calls and update_port_status calls to avoid simultaneous
attempts to acquire SQL update locks on the port table from
the same thread pool.

This semaphore has been introduced to avoid undesired eventlet

commit_message:
Add a semaphore to some ML2 operations

This patch adds a semaphore for serializing the delete port API
calls and update_port_status calls to avoid simultaneous
attempts to acquire SQL update locks on the port table from
the same thread pool.

This semaphore has been introduced to avoid undesired eventlet
yields which trigger 'lock wait timeout' errors in the DB backend;
it should have a negligible impact on the overall performance.

Change-Id: I0ec947086e533945942ae93402943dec69b218ef
Partial-Bug: 1283522

subject: Convert keyring password to str before pickle.loads()
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2014-03-13 03:27:39.000000000', 'files': ['keystoneclient/httpclient.py'], 'message': 'Convert keyring password to str before pickle.loads()

The --os-cache option on Mac OS is broken and you get the
following log message as it's trying to unpickle the auth_ref
fetched from the keyring. The auth token and service catalog
ends up being fetched every time.

WARNING:keystoneclient.httpclient:Unable to retrieve token from keyring __import__() argument 1 must be string without null bytes, not str

The fix is to whack a str() around the result of keyring.get_password()
which fixes the problem but makes me want to tear my hair out
as it's the wrong way to fix it. If you dive into the OS X
backend for the keyring module (https://bitbucket.org/kang/python-keyring-lib/src/598488b60d2148d4c44e64e9e725cde93a258c75/keyring/backends/OS_X.py?at=default) it does the following awful thing:

    # it's a weird hex password, decode it.
    return unicode_str(binascii.unhexlify(hex), 'utf-8')

UTF-8 is not a suitable encoding for possible binary data - the
keyring module assumes that a "password" is something that's a
string which IMHO is why this conversion is being performed.

According to the pickle docs, "By default, the pickle data format
uses a printable ASCII representation. This is slightly more
voluminous than a binary representation. The big advantage of
using printable ASCII (and of some other characteristics of pickle's
representation) is that for debugging or recovery purposes it
is possible for a human to read the pickled file with a standard
text editor." I guess this means that doing a str() on the result
of pickle.loads() will not cause any problems since there will be
no multi-byte sequences in the string.

Change-Id: I897e0f41aa2848fb6986aa6b12c1cea9a6c87b0c
'}]
commit_message:
Convert keyring password to str before pickle.loads()

The --os-cache option on Mac OS is broken and you get the
following log message as it's trying to unpickle the auth_ref
fetched from the keyring. The auth token and service catalog
ends up being fetched every time.

WARNING:keystoneclient.httpclient:Unable to retrieve token from keyring __import__() argument 1 must be string without null bytes, not str

The fix is to whack a str() around the result of keyring.get_password()
which fixes the problem but makes me want to tear my hair out
as it's the wrong way to fix it. If you dive into the OS X
backend for the keyring module (https://bitbucket.org/kang/python-keyring-lib/src/598488b60d2148d4c44e64e9e725cde93a258c75/keyring/backends/OS_X.py?at=default) it does the following awful thing:

    # it's a weird hex password, decode it.
    return unicode_str(binascii.unhexlify(hex), 'utf-8')

UTF-8 is not a suitable encoding for possible binary data - the
keyring module assumes that a "password" is something that's a
string which IMHO is why this conversion is being performed.

According to the pickle docs, "By default, the pickle data format
uses a printable ASCII representation. This is slightly more
voluminous than a binary representation. The big advantage of
using printable ASCII (and of some other characteristics of pickle's
representation) is that for debugging or recovery purposes it
is possible for a human to read the pickled file with a standard
text editor." I guess this means that doing a str() on the result
of pickle.loads() will not cause any problems since there will be
no multi-byte sequences in the string.

Change-Id: I897e0f41aa2848fb6986aa6b12c1cea9a6c87b0c

commit_message:
Cause wait_for heat stack-create fail fast

Add a script called wait_for_stack_ready that calls heat stack-show in a
wait_for loop waiting for either the stack to be ready or else when the stack
fails and will never be ready.

wait_for_stack_ready sets up the FAIL_MATCH_OUTPUT environment variable to
check when stack-create fails and setups a new SUCCESSFUL_MATCH_OUTPUT that
check the output from the heat stack-show for when the stack reaches the
UPDATE_COMPLETE or CREATE_COMPLETE state.

Change-Id: I7daf5010d15e458d98698fb8b7e744e2a17596b1

commit_message:
Cleanup managenement via system signal handling

Now cleanup is executed alongside with testrun code in subprocess. This
approach is more flexible and logical. To properly trigger cleanup
action signal mechanism was implemented. Also code which manages
restarting of test runs were revisited in order to tune it for
supporting new changes.

Change-Id: I5bec9cc3433b1126fb85201d9f6e5b59b29f50ce

commit_message:
Add RHEL 7 image element

This is being added as a separate element because RHEL 7 is too
different from either RHEL 6 or Fedora to share all of the
configuration they do.  It uses the redhat-common element for
pieces that are duplicated.

Some current limitations of the element:
-RHEL 7 is currently still in beta, so final image locations are
 not available.  This currently defaults to the RHEL 6.5 image,
 but that will need to be overridden using the DIB_* env vars.
-There are additional tripleo-image-elements changes that will be
 needed to be able to use this for building tripleo images.
-Open vSwitch packages are not currently available in the official
 RHEL 7 repos.
-RHEL does not support qemu without kvm acceleration, so at this
 time it cannot be used as a compute node for virtualized testing.

Change-Id: I705fd475303576525a27ce6801c673b5721792c9

commit_message:

groups and members id. Kazoo relies on the `str' type, so we just assume
it wants ASCII all the time.

commit_message:
NSX: Fix router-interface-delete returns 404 when router not in nsx

Previously, if one would run router-interface-delete and the router
was not found in NSX. Neutron would raise a 404 error and remove the interface
from the database. In this case it would be better if we did not raise
a 404 error as the caller shouldn't be aware that the backend is out of sync.

Closes-bug: #1291690

Change-Id: I2400f8b31817e6dd4bc8aa08f07e1613fc2deeae

commit_message:
Tune mysql and galera backend settings on scale

- Tune MySQL config settings to be more clouds-specific (reads much
  more common, reads:writes rate is 10(100):1)
  * Limit innodb_buffer_pool_size to 10G and set is as 30% of RAM
  * Update innodb_log_file_size as:
    * If mysql ib_logfiles do not match 25% of innodb_buffer_pool_size (max 2G),
      delete them and update innodb_log_file_size in the config appropriately;
    * Otherwise, use existing ib_logfile0 size to re-evaluate the
      innodb_buffer_pool_size config value to match its real size.
  * Reduce innodb_write_io_threads to 2/2 from 2/8
  * Use innodb_flush_log_at_trx_commit=2 for HA (was 1)
  * Raise FD imits to 102400/102400 from 22058/22058,
  * Raise max connections to 3000/4096 from 2048/2048,
  * Raise open tables limits 10000/10000 from 10000/400.
  * Lower wait_timeout to 3600/3600 (1h) from 28800/28800 (8h)
  * Adjust myisam_sort_buffer_size to 64M from 8388608 bytes
  * Adjust key_buffer_size to 64M from 16777216 bytes
- Sync Puppet galera module params for MySQL module as well
Note: doubled values should be treated as simple/HA case
CI retest

Partial blueprint: optimize-db-performance-at-scale
Change-Id: Ie341da55711e70e38116389a54bda3b4357dafe7
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Better describe the compatibility mode being echo'd

When the Cisco nexus plugin is configured on DevStack, the tempest
Neutron API test test_port_list_filter_by_router_id fails with the
following error:
     ParseError: no element found: line 1, column 0

The root cause is that the Cisco Nexus plugin model layer
is encapsulating each dictionary response from the OVS subplugin
into a list, whereas the WSGI layer is expecting a dictionary
response. The fix is not to encapsulate these responses into a list.

Closes-Bug: #1284162

commit_message:
Cisco plugin fails with ParseError no elem found

When the Cisco nexus plugin is configured on DevStack, the tempest
Neutron API test test_port_list_filter_by_router_id fails with the
following error:
     ParseError: no element found: line 1, column 0

The root cause is that the Cisco Nexus plugin model layer
is encapsulating each dictionary response from the OVS subplugin
into a list, whereas the WSGI layer is expecting a dictionary
response. The fix is not to encapsulate these responses into a list.

Change-Id: I4b589e8e5696c0eae43cafc46912b3d7f29bbdb6
Closes-Bug: #1284162

commit_message:
Store policy index in container_stat table

This used to be stored in the metadata, but it has different semantics
than metadata when it comes to replication: with metadata, newest
wins, while with policy index, oldest wins. Let's store separate
things separately.

Also, this lets us do things like reference the policy index in SQL
triggers, or have a broker method that just pulls out the policy
index without everything else.

Also also, it's faster to do it this way: you don't have to
deserialize a big blob of JSON just to pull out a single integer.

Change-Id: I26f7ef09201970ee876ac24f39d0b2d4895bfda9

commit_message:
Fix update of Health Monitors in Neutron LB Pool

This resource was using wrong way of accessing the list of old monitors,
resulting in resource references being not resolved on update.

With this fix health monitors of the pool are stored as resource data,
allowing access to the list of old (pre-update) monitors during update.

Change-Id: I0694934ee1cdfbdaa42614a66d2432dc319b3179
Closes-Bug: #1292495

commit_message:
Expose API for fetching a single driver

The API currently allows drivers to be listed, but not fetched
individually.  This patch allows drivers to be retrieved by name.
While the current implementation offers only a modest performance
advantage over simply listing all drivers, this is required by Pecan
to enable us to expose further routes beneath
/v1/drivers/<driver_name>/.

Closes-Bug: #1294869

Change-Id: Id1a0868c58abb6ab10c2e5ca65559c91795dba26

commit_message:
Add field translation to complex query from OldSample to Sample

Complex query returns the samples according to the new Sample model, but
it accepts the field names in the query expression only from the OldSample
model during the validation. This patch adds translation between the old
and new field names and translates the field names to the format of the
DB model.

Closes-bug: #1291415

commit_message:
Prevent rescheduling on block device failure

Due to a race condition - it is possible for more instances to race for
the same volume. In such a scenario, the one that fails will get
rescheduled, and in the process detach the volume of a successful
instance.

To prevent this, this patch makes nova not reschedule on block device
failures. This is actually reasonable behaviour as block device failures
are rarely related to the compute host itself and so rescheduling is not
usually useful.

This bug does not exist in the new boot code in the manager which will
be used once remove-cast-to-schedule-run-instance bp lands (see
Iefab71047996b7cc08107794d5bc628c11680a70). However, it is now clear
that this will not be merged for Icehouse, so this patch is a
"forward port" of a patch we already applied to stable/havana.

Closes-bug: #1195947

Change-Id: I6b68965ac65cdb0e1da3b44e83428f056b1693aa

commit_message:
Validate get limits attributes of Nova V2 API

Now most attributes of Nova v2/v3 APIs are not checked in Tempest,
and this patch adds some tests which check these attributes to block
the backward incompatibility change in the future.

This patch adds the checks of "get limits" API responses.

The response body of v2 API is the following:
  {
    "limits": {
      "absolute": {
        "maxTotalRAMSize": 51200,
        "totalCoresUsed": 0,
        "maxTotalInstances": 10,
        "maxTotalFloatingIps": 10,
        "totalSecurityGroupsUsed": 0,
        "maxTotalCores": 20,
        "totalFloatingIpsUsed": 0,
        "maxSecurityGroups": 10,
        "maxServerMeta": 128,
        "maxPersonality": 5,
        "maxImageMeta": 128,
        "maxPersonalitySize": 10240,
        "maxSecurityGroupRules": 20,
        "maxTotalKeypairs": 100,
        "totalRAMUsed": 0,
        "totalInstancesUsed": 0
      },
      "rate": []
    }
  }

Partially implements blueprint nova-api-attribute-test

Change-Id: I503db2986ddcafb899f16d1547fd4857d355f2ed

commit_message:
NSX plugin: Introduce operational status for security groups

This is an extension specific to the NSX plugin which introduces
the 'status' attributes for security groups. Asynchronous
operation need this attribute to set the appropriate state for
the resource according to the task completion state.

Like other attribute extensions, this extension adds a new DB
table with a 1:1 relationship with the security groups table.

Migration of this attribute to the code API in the future would
be straightforward.

Related to blueprint nvp-async-backend-commuunication

Change-Id: I5eb9e863c1b8e279c4bec70753f1fde5e4ee9339

commit_message:
Stub get_meminfo to prevent reading /proc/meminfo

We don't want to read from /proc/meminfo while running tests. It
isn't pretty and it only works on Linux.

Creates a new stubs module and updates test_hostinfo to use
it for its hostinfo.get_meminfo stub. The TestHostInfoCase
tests now use Stubs rather than assignment operators.

Change-Id: Ifbf47e0c0faebf6b52139c2b38b673a7b9310d2f
Closes-Bug: 1284990

commit_message:
Discover the docker registry port only once

The method of autodiscovering the docker registry is
slow, but only needs to be performed once. Rather than
discovering it on each spawn/snapshot/etc, we may simply
perform this discovery during host init.

Change-Id: Ic719d71c410104f2ae0343103c59bed497958318
Closes-Bug: 1286171

subject: Handle inspect containers failures
revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2014-03-06 20:28:39.000000000', 'files': ['nova/virt/docker/client.py', 'nova/tests/virt/docker/test_docker_client.py', 'nova/virt/docker/driver.py', 'nova/tests/virt/docker/test_driver.py'], 'message': "Handle inspect containers failures

Docker's client.inspect_container method may return None
if a container does not exist. As it is expected to be a
dictionary in several places in the docker driver, TypeErrors
may occur and raise unhandled Exceptions.

In the case of list_instances, this results in an
unhandled race-condition. There, we inspect a container
that existed when we begain assembling the list of instances
from the list of running containers, but containers have
been deleted and are no longer inspectable. This patch
will safely skip including those containers in the response
should their inspect_containers call return False.

Furthermore, as it is presumed the return of inspect_container will
be a dictionary, we change the result of a failed query into
an empty dictionary. This will allow successful .get() methods
for easier management of failed queries while still providing
a negative boolean response from the method ({} is False).

Change-Id: Iead7025efa024bed809640a37168174fc5354654
Closes-Bug: #1288940
"}]
commit_message:
Handle inspect containers failures

Docker's client.inspect_container method may return None
if a container does not exist. As it is expected to be a
dictionary in several places in the docker driver, TypeErrors
may occur and raise unhandled Exceptions.

In the case of list_instances, this results in an
unhandled race-condition. There, we inspect a container
that existed when we begain assembling the list of instances
from the list of running containers, but containers have
been deleted and are no longer inspectable. This patch
will safely skip including those containers in the response
should their inspect_containers call return False.

Furthermore, as it is presumed the return of inspect_container will
be a dictionary, we change the result of a failed query into
an empty dictionary. This will allow successful .get() methods
for easier management of failed queries while still providing
a negative boolean response from the method ({} is False).

Change-Id: Iead7025efa024bed809640a37168174fc5354654
Closes-Bug: #1288940

commit_message:
Add listing tested APIs

In the Icehouse design summit QA session, we've discussed "coverage
analysis tooling" and decided to refresh and use this patch[1].
This patch is for catching called Nova APIs and creating a report on
integration tests. When start catching, every called API will be caught.
To enable this function, 'api_coverage=True' is needed in nova.conf.

[1] https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/icehouse-summit-qa-coverage-tooling

blueprint: list-tested-apis
DocImpact

Change-Id: Id8ca66380f83478a335982dcf11ec9498cf223a4

commit_message:
fix cinder quota equality

The cinder quota test was of bad quality, and assumed that all
the functions in the class ran in linear order to work. If they
run in a different order the tenant could have additional quota
values beyond the strict defaults.

We can fix this by testing the returned quota contains the values
we're attempting to update.

Closes-Bug: #1291926

Change-Id: I53a154aac61368b7c20ac5703f3877fcf42f9781

commit_message:
Change report_interval from 4 to 30, agent_down_time from 9 to 75

report_interval is how often an agent sends out a heartbeat to the
service. The Neutron service responds to these 'report_state' RPC
messages by updating the agent's heartbeat DB record.
The last heartbeat is then compared to the configured
agent_down_time to determine if the agent is up or down.
The agent's status is used when scheduling networks on DHCP
and L3 agents.

In the spirit of sane defaults suited for production, these values
should be bumped to reduce the load on the Neutron service
dramatically, freeing up CPU time to perform intensive operations.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1293083
Change-Id: I77bcf8f66f74ba55513c989caead1f96c92b9832

commit_message:
Update sqlalchemy migrate scripts for postgres

pgsql <= 8.3 was lax about char->other casting but this was tightened
up in 8.4+. We must now specify the USING clause for such a cast to
succeed. The SQL queries generated by sqlalchemy for pgsql don't
support this, so an override is needed to support pgsql for the trove
migrate scripts.

Closes-bug: 1293465
Change-Id: I217fc861036911e61bafe706e338bb3b8f49e708

commit_message:
Host and service api no longer work with cells

The host and service api no longer work with
cells because in cells a host and service ID
is <cell routing path>@<ID>. While the real
id of host and service in DB must be int,
remove the operation of changing id to string.

Change-Id: I580695c3e546cd7cfc7c6dbada37fcf94759a18b
Closes-bug: #1251043

commit_message:
VMware: bug fix for host operations when using VMwareVCDriver

Currently the driver does not have a mapping between a Nova 'host'
and a VMware 'cluster'. A host operation would update the state of
one of the hosts in one of the configured clusters.

The solution is for the driver to raise a NotImplemented exception.

Change-Id: Idd78020374a6fe2d34bf8d860c30e2ed8c719903
Closes-bug: #1274129

commit_message:
Cells: Send instance object for instance_delete_everywhere

The delete method in the compute api expects an instance object to be
passed in. So the instance object needs to not be to_primitived in the
instance_delete_everywhere rpc method.

Closes-bug: #1293750

commit_message:
libvirt: handle NoneType vcpu info in get_vcpu_used

The old libvirt(e.g. 0.9.x) return None rather than -1
while get the vcpu info of a domain failed, and python-libvirt
does not raise a libvirtError exception in this situation,
this may be a libvirt bug, but we should make nova be compatible
with it.

Closes-bug: #1294509
Change-Id: Iad18d002c8e1640af049b3312783440e02a7f552

commit_message:
Stop removing ip allocations on port delete

The _delete_port() method was manually removing related
IPAllocation instances despite the existence of a perfectly
good cascade deletion relationship in the model.  This patch
puts an end to that nonsense and the potential for deadlock that
it represented.

Closes-bug: #1288379
Related-Bug: #1283522

Change-Id: Ib31550fa9000fc75768a327cb6cc1c419e06568f

subject: Fix Grizzly to Havana migration of quota_usages table
revisions:
[{'number': 3, 'created': '2014-03-19 23:49:07.000000000', 'files': ['nova/db/sqlalchemy/migrate_repo/versions/216_sync_quota_usages.py'], 'message': "Fix Grizzly to Havana migration of quota_usages table

Migration script 216 clears quota_usages table when the user_id is null
then attempts to repopulate it with data from other tables. Migration
203 adds the user_id column to quota_usages and sets them to null
initially so migration 216 will wipe the entire quota_usages table.
There's a bug in the migration since it queries the quota_usages table
for the possible resources after this table is empty.

Closes-Bug:1245746

Change-Id: I7c7948c2b4a70bc42c4a5580737dec3e8863f0d9
"}]
commit_message:
Fix Grizzly to Havana migration of quota_usages table

Migration script 216 clears quota_usages table when the user_id is null
then attempts to repopulate it with data from other tables. Migration
203 adds the user_id column to quota_usages and sets them to null
initially so migration 216 will wipe the entire quota_usages table.
There's a bug in the migration since it queries the quota_usages table
for the possible resources after this table is empty.

Closes-Bug:1245746

Change-Id: I7c7948c2b4a70bc42c4a5580737dec3e8863f0d9

commit_message:
Fix re-schedule causing attached volume conflicts

Due to re-scheduler mechanism, when a user
tries to create (in error) an instance using a volume
which is already in use by another instance,
the error is correctly detected, but the recovery code
will incorrectly affect the original instance.

Need to raise exception directly when the situation above occured.

P.S. Updated on Mar 19th:

Due to the Iefab71047996b7cc08107794d5bc628c11680a70
doesn't catch up with the Icehouse.

So we need to use the Havana patch
I6b68965ac65cdb0e1da3b44e83428f056b1693aa
to fix this issue instead.

Change-Id: Ib45c11604e167f3ee3d14874fe297beeb5a2c8ec
Closes-Bug: #1195947

commit_message:
VMware: iscsi target discovery fails while attaching volumes

VMware Drivers are unable to discover iscsi targets because
the api calls fail to specify the iscsi server location
(referred in the code as target portal) to retrieve targets.
This is critical for the attach_volume feature to work with
iscsi supported cinder drivers.

Closes-Bug: #1235112

Change-Id: I60c06ae651bb2eb6d466a5ca61a09f289c21d1a3

subject: Use strict assertion in Cinder quota update
revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2014-03-19 06:11:36.000000000', 'files': ['tempest/api/volume/admin/test_volume_quotas.py'], 'message': 'Use strict assertion in Cinder quota update

Cinder automatically creates an unlimited default quota for volume types
once the first volume is created. If volume creation tests are done
before this default quota update test, it would fail due to not knowing
about volume type quotas that were created earlier. This assertion
change just checks specifically the quotas that were updated.

Closes-Bug: #1291162
Change-Id: Iec66b89d1d7f3c9442a2e32fc931efa9a6a163d4
'}]
commit_message:
Use strict assertion in Cinder quota update

Cinder automatically creates an unlimited default quota for volume types
once the first volume is created. If volume creation tests are done
before this default quota update test, it would fail due to not knowing
about volume type quotas that were created earlier. This assertion
change just checks specifically the quotas that were updated.

Closes-Bug: #1291162

commit_message:
Fix invalid vim call in vim_util.get_dynamic_properties()

Code was calling
vim.CancelRetrievePropertiesEx(token=obj_content.token)

This will be translated into a call to
vim_request_handler(managed_object, **kwargs) by Vim.__getattr__(),
which requires a managed_object argument.

This change also adds a test for vim_util.get_dynamic_properties which
exercises both property retrieval, and the cancellation of an
unfinished RetrieveResult.

Change-Id: Ie0d98cbded4dee680593d2a950510de25ee5fab7

commit_message:
Stop test server leaking even if an error happens

Some api/compute test creates multiple test-servers in setUpClass(). But
if an error happens, some servers are not deleted because
tearDownClass() is not called.
This commit fixes it.

Partially Implements: blueprint stop-leaking

Change-Id: I448bf844a19cd88da0dd3a6da162711307e34b30

commit_message:
Add saharaclient to global requirements

The python-saharaclient 0.6.0 release is a fully renamed version of ex.
savanna client with backward compat for both python bindings and cli,
so, we're planning to switch external projects requirements to the
saharaclient package imports and sahara cli command usage and then remove
python-savannaclient from the global requirements.

Change-Id: I97ea6560580931452c8739e4f6961412c873dac1

commit_message:
Git url validation

* Adds a new InvalidInput exception for these kinds of checks

Partially implements: blueprint solum-input-validation

revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2014-03-10 15:53:33.000000000', 'files': ['tools/element_lint.sh'], 'message': "WIP: Check that scripts are set -e

WIP reason: Before I go through and fix up all of the set calls
in the elements, I want a consensus on what we should be
enforcing here.  I think -e definitely makes sense, probably -u,
and possibly -x.  -e for the reasons below, -u for similar reasons,
and -x is helpful for debugging, but it does tend to clutter up the
logs somewhat so I don't know that we want to enforce it.

When element scripts are not set -e, it's possible for failures to
be ignored and then bite us later when deploying the image.  It's
better to catch those errors when they happen.

"}]
commit_message:
WIP: Check that scripts are set -e

WIP reason: Before I go through and fix up all of the set calls
in the elements, I want a consensus on what we should be
enforcing here.  I think -e definitely makes sense, probably -u,
and possibly -x.  -e for the reasons below, -u for similar reasons,
and -x is helpful for debugging, but it does tend to clutter up the
logs somewhat so I don't know that we want to enforce it.

When element scripts are not set -e, it's possible for failures to
be ignored and then bite us later when deploying the image.  It's
better to catch those errors when they happen.

Change-Id: I3ba94d1f399df0c5bd67ba93ac7fa030a271aaa0

commit_message:
Relax regex when keystone refuses connections

Seems newer python-keystoneclient have a different excpetion message,
specifically they dropped the HTTP prefix.  Now we allow both messages to be
trapped.

Add some additional cases that are common regex now covers
 (HTTP 400)
 [Errno 111] Connection refused
 503 Service Unavailable
 Max retries exceeded
 HTTP Unable to establish connection
 Unable to establish connection to http://...

Change-Id: I71fada12b3dbb681288c7ef2891603f970910736
Signed-off-by: Paul Belanger <paul.belanger@polybeacon.com>
Signed-off-by: Andrew Woodward <awoodward@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
New SSL extension

Note: This change is a continuation of a previous change
that was abandoned due to rebase issues (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/63510)

Adding new ssl extension for ssl-termination support
in neutron.
Extension is not served by lbaas plugin
but is extending lbaas vip with ssl entities associations

Creating new abstract driver for ssl api
Adding new absract driver as a base to radware driver

Adding ssl dbmixin for ssl policies and certificates
management.
If service provider (driver) is not inheriting from new
abstract ssl driver - new "ExtensionNotSupportedByProvider"
exception is raised.

Since association of ssl certificates and vip requires
sending a list on certificates, list support was needed
in neutron resource attributes parsing mechanism.
I added the lists support and extended unit tests to test it.

Added unit tests for extension and db mixin

Alembic migration was added for the change

Radware driver and its unit tests are WIP, do not review.

Change-Id: Ie6468f0488ea2515ed8ccbe1a8c9c55b9ab4a3de
Implements: blueprint lbaas-ssl-termination

commit_message:
Change remaining 'savanna' references in sahara/tests

These changes remove the remaining 'savanna' references under the
'tests' dir to 'sahara' and modify necessary files outside of
'tests' to make unit and integration tests pass.

* Change member savanna_config to sahara_config for alembic
* Change description strings in sahara/resources
* Change exception strings in plugin validation
* Change tests/README
* Change param names, defaults, and help in integration tests config.py
* Change alembic migration test lock prefix
* Change SAVANNA_MYSQL_PRESENT and SAVANNA_TEST_POSTGRESQL_PRESENT in
  alembic tests
* Change 'Generated by' message in crypto.py

subject: Prevent attach volume race when compute is down
reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 782, 'name': 'John Garbutt', 'email': 'john.garbutt@stackhpc.com', 'username': 'johngarbutt'}, {'_account_id': 1653, 'name': 'garyk', 'email': 'gkotton@vmware.com', 'username': 'garyk'}, {'_account_id': 4393, 'name': 'Dan Smith', 'email': 'dms@danplanet.com', 'username': 'danms'}, {'_account_id': 5170, 'name': 'Microsoft Hyper-V CI', 'email': 'hyper-v_ci@microsoft.com', 'username': 'hyper-v-ci', 'tags': ['SERVICE_USER']}, {'_account_id': 5292, 'name': 'Christopher Yeoh', 'email': 'cbkyeoh@gmail.com', 'username': 'cyeoh-0'}, {'_account_id': 5511, 'name': 'Nikola Dipanov', 'email': 'ndipanov@redhat.com', 'username': 'ndipanov'}, {'_account_id': 9578, 'name': 'DB Datasets CI', 'email': 'turbo-hipster@lists.rcbops.com', 'username': 'turbo-hipster', 'tags': ['SERVICE_USER']}]
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2014-03-18 13:12:42.000000000', 'files': ['nova/exception.py', 'nova/api/openstack/compute/plugins/v3/extended_volumes.py', 'nova/tests/api/openstack/compute/plugins/v3/test_extended_volumes.py', 'nova/api/openstack/compute/contrib/volumes.py', 'nova/tests/api/openstack/compute/contrib/test_volumes.py', 'nova/compute/api.py', 'nova/tests/compute/test_compute.py'], 'message': 'Prevent attach volume race when compute is down

As described in the linked bug, if the compute service is down, and
there is a volume attach request, there is a window where
reserve_block_device rpc message may stay on the message bus, which can
cause inconsistent behaviour.

This patch introduces 2 changes that will mitigate this. The first one
is that we will check if the compute service where the instance is
running is up, and if not we will fail the request. This is a
reasonable thing to do since we cannot possibly complete the attach
request at such time and it is better to let the user know that
what he is expecting to happen cannot happen at this time. Since some
attach requests can now return a 503 HTTP status this commit will have

DocImpact

In addition, the EC2 API will now respond with an InternalError.

The second change is that we move the volume reservation before the
reserve_block_device call. This will result in volume being kept in
"attaching" state until the request completes, thus making the window
where volume can be mistaken for available while we are waiting for a
delayed RPC call much smaller.

Closes-bug: #1180040

commit_message:
Prevent attach volume race when compute is down

As described in the linked bug, if the compute service is down, and
there is a volume attach request, there is a window where
reserve_block_device rpc message may stay on the message bus, which can
cause inconsistent behaviour.

This patch introduces 2 changes that will mitigate this. The first one
is that we will check if the compute service where the instance is
running is up, and if not we will fail the request. This is a
reasonable thing to do since we cannot possibly complete the attach
request at such time and it is better to let the user know that
what he is expecting to happen cannot happen at this time. Since some
attach requests can now return a 503 HTTP status this commit will have

DocImpact

In addition, the EC2 API will now respond with an InternalError.

The second change is that we move the volume reservation before the
reserve_block_device call. This will result in volume being kept in
"attaching" state until the request completes, thus making the window
where volume can be mistaken for available while we are waiting for a
delayed RPC call much smaller.

Closes-bug: #1180040
Change-Id: I73c3ec051add59fce4053a64f42e24e74b8de71f

Ensure to count firewalls in target tenant

Previously admin tenant cannot create a firewall if other tenant
already created a firewall. We need to count firewalls only in
a target tenant.

commit_message:
Mock agent RPC for FWaaS tests to delete DB objs

This changes the firewall service unit tests to
mock the RPC calls from the firewall service to
the agent. This allows the tests to fake the
agent response RPC that removes the firewall
from the DB so the all of the other objects that
the firewall depends on can be deleted.

Closes-Bug: #1288441
Change-Id: I32462ab5557b9c52328bf6a23a12efc2d799644c

commit_message:
Remove IDENTIFIED BY clause for MySQL REVOKE

IDENTIFIED BY is not documented for REVOKE in MySQL 5.5 and 5.6 and
furthermore produces a syntax error on MySQL 5.6.

Change-Id: Ib7bf1ba0ce049c1ed8a90292064a1e05724170e0
Closes-Bug: #1292690

The first thing is to make clear that when we could put traceback in rally

----------------------------------------

[0] Server side fault

commit_message:
improve rally output (exception part)

This patch does a lot of trivial changes. But all changes belong to two
things.

The first thing is to make clear that when we could put traceback in rally
output. There is a strategy:

----------------------------------------
|  err type    |  [0]  |  [1]  |  [2]  |
| normal mode  |   N   |   N   |   N   |
| verbose mode |   N   |   N*  |   Y   |
|  debug mode  |   N   |   Y   |   Y   |
----------------------------------------

Why need the [1] between [0] and [2]? The reason is that OpenStack APIs
always return something hard to explain[3]. In another word, we need some
*hacking* for it in rally codes. At least we have to parse it in a way
different with [0] and [2].

The second thing is improving error message so that we could understand
output better. An easy example is that when updating resource status,
the old output always said "resource is in ERROR status". Who is it?
What's the reason for it? This is what this patch is trying to tell you.

Firstly some exception message is improved:

GetResourceFailture: telling users *which resource* failed and *why*
GetResourceNotFound: telling users *which resource* is not found
GetResourceErrorStatus: telling users *which resource* is in a *error
                        status* and *why* (if possible)

And print fault message of nova servers.

[0] Server side fault
[1] Client side fault caused by server side
[2] Client side fault
[3] bug #1280453

Change-Id: I3082a72b6547493ed19def83847fe8f6e9ff0e2f

commit_message:
Catch InstanceNotFound exceptions for V2 API virtual interfaces

Use the common.get_instance method to get the instance object
in the V2 API virtual interfaces extension rather than call
the compute api directly. The utility function
handes InstanceNotFound exceptions and tranlsates them to HTTPNotFound
rather than letting them propagate up causing a traceback.

Co-Authored-By: Michael Still <mikal@stillhq.com>

Change-Id: I8abee22c53195926e3d2af1da9b14cd9d3608e63
Closes-Bug: 1270804

commit_message:
Make LIVE Tests configurable with ENV

To enable ldap live test, set the environmental variable
``ENABLE_LDAP_LIVE_TESTS`` to a non-false value.

To enable tls ldap live test, set the environmental variable
``ENABLE_TLS_LDAP_LIVE_TESTS`` to a non-false value.

To enable mysql sql live test, set the environmental variable
``ENABLE_LIVE_MYSQL_TESTS`` to a non-false value.

To enable postgres sql live test, set the environmental variable
``ENABLE_LIVE_POSTGRES_TESTS`` to a non-false value.

To enable db2 sql live test, set the environmental variable
``ENABLE_LIVE_DB2_TESTS`` to a non-false value.

This allows for running all tests in a standard run by simply setting
the appropriate environmental variables.

This moves the live tests to be skips if the specific live-test
environmental variables are not set.

Change-Id: I8c09a8dcfca3f9691306c5f416f688205171bda3
Closes-Bug: 1243392

commit_message:
Enable run_ssh and add floatingip + keypair auth

Make the instance validation tests neutron and gate friendly.

The instance validation code part got several additional option, in
order to be able to use the old method when it is needed.

The old method expected the fixed/private ip externally reachable and
the shadow file on the instance is changeable by n-cpu.

The cirros image has limited data command so the uptime check is changed.
Cirros does not sets the hostname according to the metadata
so the hostname verification is skipped.
The volume+reboot test still requires the 'adminpass' auth method,
but that test case should be scenario anyway.

The ssh connection after rebooting has an issue so the
test_reboot_server_hard is skipped.

Implements: blueprint ssh-auth-strategy

Change-Id: If8e1e2cb5fc078f8c0c6308f1baf98558dbb5814

commit_message:
change dirty logs to work off a whitelist

instead of marking the logs that we think should be clean, mark
the ones we think should be dirty. This means no new services can
come in with unclean logs.

remove the whitelist data, as that's currently obsolete, we'll
remove the code for it later.

Change-Id: I4b15c932b78f54ec371aa67c7b4e8248b3f9c0eb

commit_message:
Add user-supplied arguments in log_handler

When using PublishErrorsHandler, it will missing user-supplied
arguments. For example, do LOG.info("blabla %s", "foo"),
the payload only contains "blabla %s", but we expect it like
"blabla foo". this bug has been fixed in oslo, just syncs it to
ceilometer.
Sync from Oslo, change-id: I91289cc4a60f5dab89bca852e6f52b4b83831e47

Change-Id: Ic2773035f6899e1ba7ec2813f79bd271dfa36b97

subject: Add container forwarding support to updater daemon
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2013-10-14 10:15:47.000000000', 'files': ['swift/container/updater.py', 'swift/container/sync.py', 'test/unit/common/middleware/test_keystoneauth.py', 'test/unit/container/test_sync.py', 'swift/account/server.py', 'swift/common/middleware/keystoneauth.py', 'test/unit/container/test_fwd_updater.py', 'swift/proxy/controllers/account.py'], 'message': "Add container forwarding support to updater daemon

This is one of a set of patches implementing a container-forwarding feature.
(see https://blueprints.launchpad.net/swift/+spec/cluster-federation)

Normally the updater daemon digs info out of a container DB and
PUTs it to all the account servers for the container's account.

In the case of a forwarded container the home container simply
contains a reference to a target container on another cluster
and so has 0 objects and 0 bytes itself. Updating the account
servers with 0,0 is not very useful...

So the updater daemons that runs on the home cluster and the target
cluster need to be changed to either, in the case of a home cluster,
fetch the container info from the target cluster and update the
account servers with that, or in the case of a target cluster, get
info out of the container DB and report it back to the home cluster.

The updater daemon figures out whether it's dealing with a forwarded
container by looking for 'x-container-attr-fwd-*' metadata in the
container DB. If the daemon finds a 'x-container-attr-fwd-dest' key
it's found the home part of a forwarded container and uses the value
of the 'x-container-attr-fwd-dest' key as a URL from which to fetch
info using HEAD. If the daemon finds a 'x-container-attr-fwd-src' key
it's found the target part of a forwarded container and uses the value
of the 'x-container-attr-fwd-src' key as a URL to which it reports
info using POST. [It currently does not use PUT as PUTs are only
enabled if Swift is configured to allow account management]

The reason the updater code has been modified to do both fetch and
report is two-fold:
1. Report is more efficient as reports are only sent if data has
changed.
2. Fetch could be a 'belt-and-braces' tactic to handle the cases
where report is not working. Also fetch is the only way that a missing
target container can be detected and fixed.
Note on any given cluster updater daemons can fetch OR report - they
can not do both.

By default the updater daemon acts as it always has and completely
ignores forwarded containers. To configure it to take account of
forwarded containers it needs to be configured with cf_mode 'report',
'fetch' or 'fetchfix' - the latter is an augmented fetch that cleans
up when a missing target container is detected.
The updater daemon can be configured with separate intervals for
reporting, fetching and fixing (cf_report_interval, cf_fetch_interval
and cf_fetch_fix_missing_interval). Timestamps are written into the
container DB to allow these intervals to be honoured and preserved
across multiple passes of the daemon.

To allow these modifications to work a number of other changes had to
be made:
1. swift/account/server.py translates a POST into a PUT
2. swift/proxy/controllers/account.py makes account POST a
delay_denial OP and calls swift.authorize
3. swift/common/middleware/keystoneauth.py allows the daemon
(via a secret key) to do both HEADs and POSTs
4. swift/container/sync.py is modified to prevent home containers
being sync'd elsewhere - they're empty so it's pointless
5. numerous tests

Change-Id: I95f0d0b90184f4472f70dcead75f1a8c5b789546
Implements: blueprint cluster-federation
"}]
commit_message:
Add container forwarding support to updater daemon

This is one of a set of patches implementing a container-forwarding feature.
(see https://blueprints.launchpad.net/swift/+spec/cluster-federation)

Normally the updater daemon digs info out of a container DB and
PUTs it to all the account servers for the container's account.

In the case of a forwarded container the home container simply
contains a reference to a target container on another cluster
and so has 0 objects and 0 bytes itself. Updating the account
servers with 0,0 is not very useful...

So the updater daemons that runs on the home cluster and the target
cluster need to be changed to either, in the case of a home cluster,
fetch the container info from the target cluster and update the
account servers with that, or in the case of a target cluster, get
info out of the container DB and report it back to the home cluster.

The updater daemon figures out whether it's dealing with a forwarded
container by looking for 'x-container-attr-fwd-*' metadata in the
container DB. If the daemon finds a 'x-container-attr-fwd-dest' key
it's found the home part of a forwarded container and uses the value
of the 'x-container-attr-fwd-dest' key as a URL from which to fetch
info using HEAD. If the daemon finds a 'x-container-attr-fwd-src' key
it's found the target part of a forwarded container and uses the value
of the 'x-container-attr-fwd-src' key as a URL to which it reports
info using POST. [It currently does not use PUT as PUTs are only
enabled if Swift is configured to allow account management]

The reason the updater code has been modified to do both fetch and
report is two-fold:
1. Report is more efficient as reports are only sent if data has
changed.
2. Fetch could be a 'belt-and-braces' tactic to handle the cases
where report is not working. Also fetch is the only way that a missing
target container can be detected and fixed.
Note on any given cluster updater daemons can fetch OR report - they
can not do both.

By default the updater daemon acts as it always has and completely
ignores forwarded containers. To configure it to take account of
forwarded containers it needs to be configured with cf_mode 'report',
'fetch' or 'fetchfix' - the latter is an augmented fetch that cleans
up when a missing target container is detected.
The updater daemon can be configured with separate intervals for
reporting, fetching and fixing (cf_report_interval, cf_fetch_interval
and cf_fetch_fix_missing_interval). Timestamps are written into the
container DB to allow these intervals to be honoured and preserved
across multiple passes of the daemon.

To allow these modifications to work a number of other changes had to
be made:
1. swift/account/server.py translates a POST into a PUT
2. swift/proxy/controllers/account.py makes account POST a
delay_denial OP and calls swift.authorize
3. swift/common/middleware/keystoneauth.py allows the daemon
(via a secret key) to do both HEADs and POSTs
4. swift/container/sync.py is modified to prevent home containers
being sync'd elsewhere - they're empty so it's pointless
5. numerous tests

Change-Id: I95f0d0b90184f4472f70dcead75f1a8c5b789546
Implements: blueprint cluster-federation
